{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 About\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Drum Pad Mapper} is a JSFX plugin that lets the user remap der drum pads in an intuitive and playful way via a graphical user interface.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Manual\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Sliders\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Drum Pad Midi Channel\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This slider specifies the drum pad\u8217's MIDI channel. Set this to the output channel of your drum pad.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Set Output Midi Channel\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This slider specifies which channel/s to listen to when setting any pad\u8217's \u8220"OUT\u8221" value.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Unmapped Pad Behaviour\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This sliders specifies whether to allow unmapped MIDI notes to pass through or not.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Pad Count\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This slider specifies how many pads there are on your physical drum pad.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Pads Per Row\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This slider specifies how many pads to display per row. This assumes a rectangular pad arrangement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Registering a pad\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In order to register a pad\u8217's input note (for example the top left-hand-side pad) simply {\f1 right-click} it with your mouse. This arms the pad for selection. You can now trigger the respective physical drum pad that the virtual one should represent (in our example, the top left-hand-side one). {\f1 Right-click} the pad again to disarm the pad without changing anything.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After registering all pads, you may want to save the layout as a preset in REAPER.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Mapping a pad to a note\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The process of mapping a pad to a note is similar to registering a pad. {\f1 Left-click} the desired pad with your mouse to arm it and then press the respective key on your MIDI device. {\f1 Left-click} the pad again to disarm the pad without changing anything.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Removing a mapping\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In order to remove a mapping, simply hold {\f1 Ctrl} on {\i Windows} or {\f1 Cmd} on {\i OSX} use either the {\f1 left-} or {\f1 right mouse-button} to un-map or unregister a pad.\par}
}

